I want to recognize that all I have shared here is built on the shoulders of giants in the world of engineering, regenerative agriculture and biochar. I am working to bring it from a niche into a mainstream part of our economy by bringing talent and capital to it.

At scale, these bioreactors remove carbon as a happy byproduct of a profitable industrial process. The revenue streams of waste removal, green energy and carbon products (biochar, activated carbon, etc) make the math work even if there is no carbon credit revenue.

At scale, we can use this biochar to repair the soil depleted by industrial agriculture around the world and even make desert regions fertile. One acre of soil can store more than 10 tons of biochar, giving us the one carbon sink large enough to actually solve global warming.

This machine is designed to manufactured using the same tools and materials as the automotive industry. By making it modular, we can take it to wherever biomass waste accumulates. By leveraging mass production, we can make it far more affordable than large custom plants.

To make a dent in the carbon balance of the planet, these reactors must:Be manufacturable at automotive scale.Be decentralized globally.Produce economically useful commodities as outputs.Leverage waste feedstocks as inputs.Generate the bulk of their own energy.

This is a containerized modular bioreactor. It uses pyrolysis to convert wood waste into biochar and biogas. Biochar is incredibly useful and valuable, most particularly as a way to add carbon back to soil. Biogas can generate green heat, electricity and even hydrogen. https://t.co/EAiZp2BcP7

It can be, but here's where we need technology. We need to capture the carbon in a form that is economically useful and will stay in the ground. We also need to utilize the green energy embodied in tree and plant agricultural waste. That's the technology I am building.

Carbon is not only captured by trees. Agriculture captures an enormous amount of carbon. Rice husks are 34% carbon. Wheat husks are 39% carbon. Coconut Shells are 50% carbon. Agriculture is carbon neutral today - but what if it could be massively carbon negative?

Carbon dioxide is only 0.04% of the atmosphere. Yet the carbon content of a tree is around 50% carbon. Carbon is only 27% of the weight of a CO2 molecule. So the pure carbon in a tree represents almost 2x the weight of the tree itself in terms of CO2 sequestered. (50% * 1/.27)

Luckily for us, there is one thing that literally eats CO2: plants. The core reaction of photosynthesis transforms CO2 + sunlight into glucose and oxygen. It naturally splits the oxygen from the carbon in CO2 and captures the carbon in physical form. https://t.co/5z1CZWP2Oy

Today, we have an almost incomprehensible amount of carbon in our sky.1 TRILLION tons of CO2 in the atmosphere need to go somewhere. (all living things weigh 0.4% of this)We only have expensive, inefficient ways to pull it out, and no clear idea where we would put it.

Humans have a rich history of amending our soil with carbon.Over 2,500 years ago, Amazonian tribes buried charcoal with food scraps. It transformed marginal soil into incredibly rich, fertile soil.The carbon they buried (as charcoal) is still there today.

At @USC_Econ , I want to work with students  who do applied adaptation research.  What microeconomic factors explain slow adaptation? Imagination? Risk preferences, under-estimating risk probabilities?  Liquidity constraints? Perverse subsidies?  durable capital?  Market power?

Back in 1985, Gary Becker sketched out a Coasian answer to this question.  Young people should revisit his hypothesis and test it in nations around the world that seek to reduce the physical risks caused by climate change.  https://t.co/s03WjXMtjl

Ahyan explicitly writes out the optimization problem and this allows him to study how each person's behavior changes as a function of government policy.  Political economy issues arise.  As climate change physical risks rise, will government reform inefficient rules of the game?

Reduced form work struggles with explaining mechanisms.  Why do we observe a past correlation?  Will such a correlation vanish in the future as the "rules of the game change"?   The Lucas Critique says "let's look at the optimizing first order conditions".

Using this reduced form empirical approach, the adaptation hypothesis is tested by observing that the damage caused by a weather event declines across time or is smaller for specific areas in the cross-section. https://t.co/gmyFbAy5p3

Most studies that seek to measure climate change damage report reduced form estimates that correlate past climate realizations with measures of economic outcomes.  For example, I have written about the death toll from past natural disasters.  https://t.co/E3PAvFsHNv

Overall, there are many factors to climate change and many solutions as well for each one. Here is my input of things I would like to point out that really impact climate change.

Overusing electricity is another huge contributor to climate change. Many think of saving electricity as in saving money. But it is also saving us from climate change. Turning off lights especially when big buildings are not in use. Making use of solar panels is a great option.

Businesses and industries have been doing whatever they can to produce the best products without considering the harmful effects to our environment. Lots of goods have been manufactured from burning fossil fuels. People should really learn about a product's manufacturing process.

Making policies about saving trees is a solution at the global scale. Locally, we all can promote gardening. Each of us can try our best to grow various plants in the garden. Whether its as small as indoor plants or plants in pots hooked up on roofs, it could definitely help.

Eliminating all the beautiful forests and cutting up all the biodiversity releases lots of carbon dioxide that has been stored in the trees. We also need natural biomes to help absorb the large amounts of carbon emissions. We should work with the government to make policies.
These are not mutually exclusive. We can also reduce cold related deaths by improving building insulation and standars. This has the added benefits of reducing energy costs and CO2 emissions.
